div.p:
Since the Treaty of Utrecht, they have ſettled a conſiderable Village on both Sides the River Chaudiere;
               The River Chaudiere empties itſelf into the River St. Lawrence, on the South Side, a League and an half above the City of Quebec.
                At ſome Leagues diſtance from the Southerly Bank of the River St. Lawrence, about twenty Leagues up this River (Chaudiere) there is a Land Carriage of a few Miles to the River Kennebeck. At this Place, if they have not already built a Fort, there has been good Intelligence that they had deſigned one. From hence the whole Force of Canada might, in a few Days, be poured into the Eaſtern Parts of the Colony of the Maſſachuſetts-Bay; the great Nurſery of Trees for Maſts, Yards, and Bowſprits, for the Royal Navy.
